
[1]onomatopy

   ON'OMATOPY, n. [Gr. name, and to make.]

   1. In grammar and rhetoric, a figure in which words are formed to
   resemble the sound made by the thing signified; as, to buzz, as bees;
   to crackle, as burning thorns or brush.

   2. A word whose sound corresponds to the sound of the thing signified.
